# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: balaclava-clothing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:balaclava-clothing/agal-accessory] An **agal** (Arabic: عِقَال; also spelled **iqal**, **egal**, or **igal**) is a clothing accessory traditionally worn by tribal Arab men.
[src:balaclava-clothing/agal-accessory] It is a doubled black cord used to keep a keffiyeh in place on the wearer's head.
[src:balaclava-clothing/agal-accessory] Agals are traditionally made of goat or camel hair.
[src:balaclava-clothing/agal-accessory] Modern agals typically use cord manufactured for this purpose (rulers of Bahrain in particular are known for wearing elaborate agal designs), but plain rope is still occasionally utilized.
[src:balaclava-clothing/agal-accessory] It is traditionally worn by Arabs from the Arabian Peninsula (except Yemen and Oman), Iraq, Jordan, tribes in Syria, Sinai and Sharqia in Egypt, the south of the Maghreb, parts of Palestine, the Negev in Israel, and Khuzestan in Iran.
[src:balaclava-clothing/agal-accessory] The use of the agal and ghutra is depicted in bas-reliefs and statues across the Middle East dating as far back as ancient times.
[src:balaclava-clothing/agal-accessory] In his book *Iran in the Ancient East*, the archaeologist and Iranologist Ernst Herzfeld, in referring to the Susa bas-reliefs, points to the ancient agal as unique headwear of Elamites that distinguished them from other nations.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] The term **aigrette** (pronounced /eɪɡrɛt/; from the French for egret, or *lesser white heron*) refers to the tufted crest or head-plumes of the egret, used for adorning a headdress.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] The word may also identify any similar ornament, in gems.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] Aigrettes, studded with diamonds and rubies, decorated the turbans of Ottoman sultans or the ceremonial chamfron of their horses.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] Several of these aigrettes are on display in the Treasury of the Topkapı Palace in Istanbul, Turkey.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] An aigrette was also formerly worn by certain ranks of officers in the French army.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] Jewelled aigrettes and "diamond feathers" worn at the English court of James VI and I and Anne of Denmark are associated with the goldsmith Arnold Lulls whose book of designs still survives.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] The 61.50 carat (12.3 g) whiskey-coloured diamond, "The Eye of the Tiger", was mounted by Cartier in a turban aigrette for the *Jam Sahib* or Maharajah of Nawanagar in 1934.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] The yellow 137.27 carat Florentine Diamond was last set as a part of an aigrette.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] The word *aigrette* is used to describe several things with a similar shape.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] It is the name given to a type of deep-fried fritter made of batter in an elongated shape.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] By analogy the word is used in various sciences for feathery excrescences of like appearance, as for the tufts on the heads of insects, the feathery down of the dandelion, the luminous rays at the end of electrified bodies, or the luminous rays—seen in solar eclipses—diverging from the moon's edge.
[src:balaclava-clothing/aigrette] The Chelengk and Sarpech were similar Turkish military decoration.
[src:balaclava-clothing/animal-hat] An **animal hat** is a novelty hat made to resemble an animal or other character.
[src:balaclava-clothing/animal-hat] It is often similar to a beanie, with facial features, added ears and sometimes details such as whiskers, although versions made from fake fur are also known by this name.
[src:balaclava-clothing/animal-hat] While they were known before 2010, animal hats became an American fashion trend in the winter of 2010-11.
[src:balaclava-clothing/animal-hat] Despite ongoing criticism, including the animal hat being listed as a 2012 fashion faux pas despite also being a "serious fashion statement," they stayed popular into 2013.
[src:balaclava-clothing/animal-hat] Books dedicated exclusively to knitting and crocheting various styles of animal hats have been published.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] An **"Anthony Eden" hat**, or simply an **"Anthony Eden"**, was a type of headgear popularised in Britain in the mid-20th century by politician Anthony Eden.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Eden, who was known for his sartorial elegance, favoured a silk-brimmed, black felt homburg at a time when most Britons preferred the trilby or the bowler.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Eden held a number of cabinet posts in the 1930s and the 1940s, and was Prime Minister from 1955 to 1957.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] The hat became so associated with him that it was commonly known in the UK as the "Anthony Eden" (or, in London's Savile Row, simply as the "Eden").
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] It came into particular vogue among civil servants and diplomats in Whitehall and, to that extent, rather belied the stereotypical view, that lasted until well after the Second World War, of civil servants as a "bowler hat" brigade.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] The homburg had initially been popularised in Britain by King Edward VII who often visited Bad Homburg in Germany.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] It was essentially a more rigid variant of the trilby which had been fashionable since George du Maurier's novel of that name was published in 1894.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In such circumstances Eden's adherence to the homburg seemed fresh and dashing.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] He is one of only two British Prime Ministers to have had an item of clothing named after him, the other being the Duke of Wellington (his boot).
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Eden became, at 38, the youngest Foreign Secretary since William Pitt the Younger in the late 18th century.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] As a relatively youthful politician among mostly much older men, he appeared fashionably dressed, even flamboyant.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In 1936 the American magazine *Time* referred to his "pin-stripe trousers, modish short jacket and swank black felt hat", worn during a diplomatic mission to the League of Nations in Geneva.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Many remarked too on Eden's "film star" appeal, even as late as the 1950s when, as Prime Minister, he retained his youthful good looks.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] When Eden visited New York City in 1938 he was "deluged with fan mail from teenage college girls to elderly matrons", while women reporters and society editors "gushed about his classic features, his long dark eyelashes, his limpid eyes, his clear skin, his wavy hair, his charm and magnetism".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In another American city, a display of homburgs in a shop window was adorned with the sign "Welcome to Anthony Eden".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In Amsterdam the hat became known as the "Lord Eden".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] The journalist Malcolm Muggeridge, who was not an admirer of Eden, recalled that, among other qualities, "an elegant appearance and an earnest disposition ... equipped him for dazzling advancement ...
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] What came to be known as an Anthony Eden hat grew on heads like his".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In June 1938, four months after Eden's resignation from Neville Chamberlain's Cabinet, the Member of Parliament and diarist "Chips" Channon noted that he had "doffed his bowler" to Chamberlain in St.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] James's Park and that "everyone wears a bowler now ... [Si]nce the Eden debacle black homburgs are "out"".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] However, in August of that year, the British Minister in Prague, Basil Newton, wore "a black homburg of the kind made fashionable by Anthony Eden" to greet Lord Runciman on his arrival by train at Wilson station for talks with the Czechoslovak government.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In 1939, writing to a former classmate during a European tour, the future United States President John F.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Kennedy remarked that he had not been doing much work, "but have been sporting around in my morning coat, my 'Anthony Eden' black homburg and white gardenia".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] There were those who believed, like Muggeridge, that Eden's rapid rise through the political hierarchy owed as much to image as to substance.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In the period between his resignation and his return to the government on the outbreak of war in 1939, Eden and his acolytes, who, broadly speaking, favoured a tougher stance against Adolf Hitler and Benito Mussolini, were often referred to as "the glamour boys".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Harold Nicolson, a member of this group who found Eden's approach ineffectual, observed that Eden was missing "every boat with exquisite elegance".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Some contemporary observers thought they detected a "prima donna" streak in Eden's attitude and appearance.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] For example, the ageing Earl of Crawford and Balcarres (1871–1940), a snob, thought him "vain as a peacock and all the mannerisms of a *petit maître* [in the sense of a dandy or fop]".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Grigg, who rarely had a good word to say of anyone, dismissed him as "a poor feeble little pansy".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Deedes, a Minister in Eden's Government who, as a journalist, had once commented unfavourably on the colour of Eden's socks, remarked half a century later that, in the modern vernacular, Eden would have been called a "smoothie".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] The philosopher Bertrand Russell thought Eden "not a gentleman" because he dressed "too well", while a Ministerial colleague R.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Butler, alluding to Eden's parentage and highly strung nature, is said to have remarked, "that's Anthony – half mad baronet, half beautiful woman".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Wilson, who observed in 2008 that Eden was "easily the best-looking individual, of either sex, to occupy [the] office [of Prime Minister] in the twentieth century", noted also that he was "the only male Prime Minister known to have varnished his fingernails".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] However, there is little objective evidence that Eden was unduly vain about his clothes; he merely dressed well.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] As for his homburg, which Deedes noted that he wore at an angle, his official biographer Sir Robert Rhodes James, wrote that "to him it was just a hat".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] The hat became a "trademark" in the public mind, assisting instant recognition, and was one of the most recognisable features of contemporaneous political cartoons.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] During the general election campaign in 1955, when Eden was Prime Minister, he was presented with "an Eden hat" when he and Lady Eden (he became a Knight of the Garter in 1954) visited the Lancashire hat-making town of Atherton.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] At various points of the Suez Crisis the following year, cartoons depicted him in the same hat for which he had become known twenty years earlier.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In one by Vicky for the *New Statesman*, a behatted but otherwise barely clothed Eden was shown in the biblical Garden of Eden being tempted with an apple by a young Frenchwoman, presumably Marianne, in the guise of Eve.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In 1951, two days after Eden's re-appointment as Foreign Secretary, Vicky had, in similar vein, employed the imagery of Antony and Cleopatra to represent Eden approaching the Egyptian throne in suit and hat.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] King Farouk (overthrown in 1952) and the ancient Queen Cleopatra, as the embodiment of the Egyptian state, were shown to have torn up the treaty of 1936 which provided for Britain's military presence in the Suez Canal zone.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] The caption, "Hush! here comes Anthony", was taken from Shakespeare.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Journalist and social historian Anne de Courcy has written of Chamberlain that "he did not smoke a pipe, nor, as Anthony Eden did, always wear the same distinctive hat, though cartoonists made the most of his ever-present umbrella".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] (On Guy Fawkes Night 1938 the future Prime Minister Harold Macmillan, then a rebellious Conservative MP, burned an image of Chamberlain with rolled umbrella, which he topped with his own homburg.) In fact, as photographs from the late 1930s onwards show, Eden frequently wore no hat at all.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] This was a habit that he shared with few other public men at the time.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] The Anthony Eden hat was essentially an accessory of the 1930s and 1940s, although, in the mid-1950s, the homburg came to be associated with the melancholic image of comedian Tony Hancock.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Sowter) in John Dighton's play *The Happiest Days of Your Life* had been described as "soberly dressed.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] He wears an "Anthony Eden" hat and carries gloves".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] As the communist historian Eric Hobsbawm put it, "Suez and the coming of rock-and-roll divide twentieth century British history".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In the 1960s, when hats for men were becoming unfashionable, former diplomat Geoffrey McDermott asked, with evident disdain, "who wears an Anthony Eden hat today?
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Only Mr Steptoe [a character in a BBC television sitcom], Mr Enoch Powell and, rather curiously, [Russian leader] Mr Kosygin.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] And, of course, all those Carleton-Browne characters at the F[oreign] O[ffice]".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Another well-known wearer of an "Anthony Eden" was Sergeant Arthur Wilson (played by John Le Mesurier) in *Dad's Army* (1968–77), the BBC TV comedy series about the wartime Home Guard, which Eden established in 1940.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In one episode, Captain Mainwaring (Arthur Lowe), who, as manager of a bank, wore a bowler, told Wilson that his hair was too long.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] Wilson replied that "Mrs Pike [his lover] says it makes me look like Eden".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anthony-eden-hat] In 1969 the Kinks recorded for their album *Arthur (Or the Decline and Fall of the British Empire)* a song called "She's Bought a Hat Like Princess Marina".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-flash-gear] Anti-flash gear protects the head, neck, face and hands from short-duration flame exposure and heat.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-flash-gear] This equipment is donned by shipboard navy personnel whenever a fire breaks out or during periods of heightened readiness.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-flash-gear] Anti-flash gear was introduced in the Royal Navy following the Battle of Jutland during the First World War, when a number of British warships had been destroyed or damaged by flash from burning cordite propellant passing through the shell handling room into the magazine.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-flash-gear] It was found that the anti-flash hoods and gloves were more effective if flame-proofed with borax or boric acid.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] During the COVID-19 pandemic, jurisdictions with pre-existing anti-mask laws exempted their mandates on face coverings from such laws, at least in practice.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] There are anti-mask laws in many U.S. states and the District of Columbia.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] These laws have been challenged on the grounds that they violate the guarantees of the First Amendment to the United States Constitution to free speech and free association.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Some courts have weighed freedom of speech against the public safety interest, and upheld such laws.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] For example, the Georgia Supreme Court found the law constitutional on the grounds that the wearing of the mask was an act of intimidation and a threat of violence, which is not protected speech.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] That law has exceptions for holiday celebrations, theatre performances, and occupational safety; the ruling makes it unclear if someone is violating the law if they wear a mask without the intent to threaten violence.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] A three-judge panel of the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit upheld a New York law on the ground that wearing a Ku Klux Klan mask did not convey a protected message beyond that conveyed by wearing a hood and robe.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Other courts have struck down anti-mask laws.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] For example, Tennessee and Florida state laws have been invalidated on the grounds that they were unconstitutionally broad.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] An ordinance in Goshen, Indiana, was struck down based on First Amendment doctrine that specifically protects anonymous speech and anonymous association, especially for unpopular groups like the KKK.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The book *Privacy on the Margins* discusses how the use of masks can be a performative act of speech and thus protected by the first amendment.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In September 2025, California passed a law that prohibits local and federal law enforcement from wearing face masks while conducting operations.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The law was passed as a response to the use of face masks by Immigrations and Customs Enforcement (ICE) during enforcement operations.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] New York State's anti-mask law was enacted in 1845, to provide for public safety after disputes between landlords and tenants.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Since 2024, a number of counties in the state have implemented or considered reintroducing the pre-COVID anti-mask law.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Nassau County implemented its current anti-mask law in August 2024 although there are exception for health and religious reasons.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The present table provides a non-exhaustive overview comparing legal restrictions of face coverings in European states.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In Austria since 2002, masking ban on demonstrations under § 9 of the Assembly Law (Versammlungsgesetz).
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Violation of the ban need not be prosecuted if the mask does not threaten public order and security.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Violation of the ban entails, according to § 19a.b of the Law, imprisonment up to six months, repeated offenses one year or a fine.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The measure took effect in October 2017.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Shortly after the enactment on 1 October 2017, there were some incidents in which people were incorrectly fined by the police, leading some commentators to point out flaws in the law, or incorrect understanding of it amongst the police.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] A Belgian law adopted in June 2011 prohibits appearing in public "with a face masked or hidden, in whole or in part, in such a way as to be unidentifiable".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Violations can result in fines and up to seven days in jail.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 11 July 2017 the ban in Belgium was upheld by the European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) after having been challenged by two Muslim women who claimed their rights had been infringed.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Wearing masks or other objects that cover the face in a way where identification is prevented during assemblies in a public place is illegal in Denmark.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The Danish Penal Code § 134 b, effective from 3 June 2000, makes the violation punishable by a fine or up to six months imprisonment.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Part 2 of § 134 b further criminalizes the possession of effects which must be viewed as intended to be used for masking in an assembly.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The §134 b, part 3, exempts from penalty masking which is done to protect one's face against the weather or worn for another worthy purpose.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The ban does not apply in the autonomous territories of Greenland or the Faroe Islands.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] 2 Versammlungsgesetz it is prohibited to disguise one's identity in public meetings such as demonstrations so as to prevent identification by police.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] This violation can be fined with imprisonment up to one year.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In Italy, a law issued in 1975 strictly forbids wearing of any attire that could hide the face of a person.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Penalties (fines and imprisonment) are provided for such behaviour.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The original purpose of the anti-mask law was to prevent crime or terrorism.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The law allows for exemptions for a "justified cause", which has sometimes been interpreted by courts as including religious reasons for wearing a veil, but others –including local governments– disagree and claim religion is not a "justified cause" in this context.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In Latvia, a law issued in 2016 to ban niqab and burqa in entire country was passed by Latvian parliament.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In the Netherlands, a first attempt towards a partial prohibition on face covering was made from 2012 to 2015, but the bill was struck down.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] A new attempt was made in the years after when a new bill was submitted on 27 November 2015.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Eventually a limited anti-mask law was passed on 26 June 2018.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] It is illegal to wear clothing which covers the entire face, or covered up to the point where only the eyes are uncovered, or renders the face unrecognisable, on public transport and in buildings and associated yards of educational institutions, governmental institutions and healthcare institutions.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Frequently cited examples are a full face helmet, a balaclava, a burqa or a niqāb.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 26 June 2018, the bill was passed in the Dutch Senate.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Concealment of faces in public is legal in Norway, except when taking part in a public event.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Exempted from the prohibition of concealment in public events are participants in theatre, masquerade or similar.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In accordance with the Norwegian police law, violation is punishable by a fine or up to three months imprisonment.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The punishment for the violation of the given law was introduced in July 2014 and is provided by the federal code on administrative offences.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] According to the November 2013 *Citizens' Security Law* (*Ley mordaza*), demonstration protesters who cover their faces may be fined up to €30,000.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] According to the 2005 'Law on the Prohibition of masking in some cases', it is prohibited for participants in the demonstration to fully or partially cover the face in a way that complicates identification.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] This prohibition applies only if there are disturbances of public order at demonstrations, or if there is an immediate danger of such disturbances.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The ban does not apply to the covering of the face for religious reasons.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] It also does not apply to the extent participants are authorized (under 2 Ch.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] 7 a § Order Act) to fully or partially cover the face.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Gallen (2009), there are laws banning use of masks .
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In a referendum on 7 March 2021, Swiss voters approved a nationwide ban on face concealment, with over 51% of the electorate supporting it.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Several days after Berkut riot police clashed with Euromaidan protesters, Verkhovna Rada enacted law 721-VII banning wearing masks, helmets or camouflage clothing by people taking part in a gathering, assembly, demonstration, protest, rally or other mass event.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Fines for violating are monetary up to about $400 or administrative arrest up to 15 days.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] For a century, covering or blacking one's face was a criminal act that could lead to the death penalty; the 1723 Black Act was repealed in 1823.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] It is legal to wear a mask in public in Australia.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Motorcycle riders wearing full face helmets are generally required to remove them when entering a bank.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] A judge in New South Wales has ruled that a woman cannot give evidence in a niqāb.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] A Victorian judge extended the ban to wearing a niqāb in the public gallery.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 4 October 2019, the Government of Hong Kong invoked the rarely used colonial-era Emergency Regulations Ordinance to implement the Prohibition on Face Covering Regulation (PFCR), an anti-mask law in response to the ongoing protest that year.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The law bans protesters from covering their faces whether in full or partially during protests, including at rallies given a "Letter of No Objection" under the Public Order Ordinance.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Anyone who wears a mask at a lawful rally or march, unlawful or unauthorised assembly, or during a riot could be sentenced to up to a year in jail and a fine of HK$25,000.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Exemptions include those at protests wearing masks for professional or paid work, or for religious or medical reasons.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In addition, the law states that anyone who disobeys a police order to remove a mask could be sentenced to six months in jail and a HK$10,000 fine.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] Paint is also included in the definition of "face-covering".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The legislation went into effect from midnight on 5 October until further notice, and the Hong Kong High Court refused to rule out an interim injunction order but the court will later decide whether to allow a judicial review into the invocation of the Emergency Regulations Ordinance.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In response to the government's implementation of the law, netizens widely shared a speech by Edward Leung in a televised debate during the 2016 Legco election, "A few years ago, Ukraine passed an anti-mask law.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 18 November 2019, the High Court ruled s3(1)(b), (c), (d) and s5 of the PFCR failed the proportionality test as they placed restrictions on fundamental rights beyond intended goals.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The court also ruled that the ERO sections empowering the Chief-Executive-in Council to make laws "on any occasion of public danger" is incompatible with multiple articles of the Hong Kong Basic Law, however, constitutional status is open to question.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] The court also held the ordinance meets the "prescribed by law" requirement.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] In response, the government said that it would stop enforcing the ban for the time being.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] A spokesman from the Chinese legislative affairs commission, however, stated that "Whether the laws of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region comply with the Basic Law of Hong Kong can only be judged and decided by the standing committee of the National People's Congress".
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 26 November 2019, the High Court announced hearing for the government appeal against the judgement is on 9 January 2020.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 27 November 2019, the Court of Appeal extended the interim suspension of the judgment until 10 December 2019.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 10 December 2019, the Court of Appeal refused to suspend the "unconstitutional" ruling by the Court of First Instance on the anti-mask regulation.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] A full hearing was scheduled to commence on 9 January 2020.
[src:balaclava-clothing/anti-mask-laws] On 21 December 2020, it was ruled by the Court of Final Appeal that the prohibition on the use of face coverings was constitutional.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] The **apex** (plural: *apices*) was a cap worn by certain priests (the flamines and Salii) in ancient Rome.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] The essential part of the apex, to which alone the name properly belonged, was a pointed piece of olive-wood called diminutively an *apicula*, the base of which was surrounded with a lock of wool.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] The flamines were forbidden by law to go into public - or even into the open air - without the apex, and hence we find the expression of *alicui apicem dialem imponere* used as equivalent to the appointment of a *Flamen Dialis*.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] Sulpicius was deprived of the priesthood, only because the apex fell from his head whilst he was sacrificing.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] Dionysius of Halicarnassus describes the cap as being of a conical form.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] On ancient monuments it can appear round or conical.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] The **albogalerus**, or **albus galerus** was a white cap worn by the *flamen dialis*, made of the skin of a white victim sacrificed to Jupiter, and had the apex fastened to it by means of an olive-twig.
[src:balaclava-clothing/apex-headdress] From the word *apex* was formed the epithet *apicatus*, applied to the *flamen dialis* by Ovid.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] A **balaclava**, also called a **ski mask** or a **racing mask**, is a piece of cloth headgear designed to expose only part of the face, usually the eyes and mouth.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Depending on style and how it is worn, only the eyes, mouth and nose, or just the front of the face are unprotected.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Versions with enough of a full face opening may be rolled into a hat to cover the crown of the head or folded down as a collar around the neck.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] It is commonly used in alpine skiing, snowboarding, motorsport and motorcycle racing.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Similar styles of headgear were known in the 19th century as the *Uhlan cap* worn by Polish and Prussian soldiers, and the *Templar cap* worn by outdoor sports enthusiasts.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] The name comes from their use at the 1854 Battle of Balaclava during the Crimean War, referring to the town of Balaklava near Sevastopol in Crimea, where British troops there wore knitted headgear to keep warm.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Handmade balaclavas were sent over to the British troops to help protect them from the bitter cold weather.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] The troops required this aid, as their own supplies (warm clothing, weatherproof quarters, and food) never arrived in time.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] According to Richard Rutt in his *History of Handknitting*, the name "balaclava helmet" was not used during the war but appears much later, in 1881.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Thin Balaclavas can be used under motorcycle, snowmobile, ski, and snowboard helmets for warmth in cool or winter conditions.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Many skiers, snowboarders, cyclists, and runners wear balaclavas in cold weather for warmth.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] They protect the head, face, and neck from wind and low temperatures and can fit easily under helmets.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] These sports balaclavas can be full balaclavas, which cover the entire head leaving only the eyes uncovered, or half-balaclavas, which leave the forehead free, but cover most of the head.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Key elements of sports balaclavas are that they are warm, windproof, and moisture-wicking.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Race drivers in Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile sanctioned events must wear balaclavas made of fire-retardant material underneath their crash helmets.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Balaclavas are in certain contexts associated with criminality as gang members have used them to conceal their identity.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] In 2004, police in Prestwich, England, began demanding that people on the street remove their balaclavas, describing the garment as "extremely threatening".
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] In 2008, police in Kent confiscated a copy of the *War on Terror* board game partly because of the inclusion of a balaclava, stating that it "could be used to conceal someone's identity or could be used in the course of a criminal act".
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] The Australian band TISM utilised balaclavas as part of their onstage image and to conceal their identities.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Often adorning their balaclavas with added features such as spikes.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] In similar fashion, the Russian feminist and performance art group Pussy Riot, also utilised colourful balaclavas, in order to remain anonymous, which became part of their image, with one member stating "You put on the mask – and you become Pussy Riot.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] In South Asia, balaclavas are commonly referred to as **monkey caps** because of their typical earth tone colours, and the fact that they blot out most human facial features.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Monkey caps sometimes have a small, decorative, woollen pom-pom on top.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] They are commonly worn by troops on Himalayan duty for protection from the cold.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] In December 2006, the United States Marine Corps began issuing balaclavas with hinged face guards as part of the Flame Resistant Organizational Gear program.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] In the Soviet Union, the balaclava became a part of standard OMON (special police task force) uniform as early as the Perestroyka years of the late 1980s.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] The original intent was to protect the identity of the officers to avoid intimidation from Russian organized crime.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Because of increased problems with organized crime of the 1990s, TV shots of armed men in black balaclavas became common.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Armed Russian police commonly conduct raids and searches of white-collar premises (typically in Moscow) while wearing balaclavas.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Such raids have therefore come to be known in Russia as "maski shows", an allusion to a popular comic TV show of the 1990s.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Balaclavas are often used by police battling drug cartels and gangs in Latin America to conceal their identity and protect their families.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Knitted balaclavas were featured in some collections at the 2018 New York Fashion Week.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] Balaclavas gained newfound popularity as a fashion accessory in many cities in the United States during the early 2020s.
[src:balaclava-clothing/balaclava-clothing] It is often colloquially referred to as a "shiesty", popularized by rapper Pooh Shiesty.
